SD|15000|SAU|round=yes}}|}}) (unlimited)\n|-\n| International Dollar Currency Card (IDC)\n| {{Currency|3000|USD}} ({{Currency|0|USD}} for the first additional card member, {{Currency|1500|USD}} for each additional card member thereafter) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|5000|USD}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/content/dam/amex/us/staticassets/pdf/cardmember-agreements/centurion-idc/idc-centurion-09-30-2019.pdf|title=Cardmember Agreement - The Centurion\u00ae Card - International Dollar Card|date=2019-09-30|accessdate=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| International Euro Currency Card (IEC)\n| {{Currency|4000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4000|DEU|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|4000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4000|DEU|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Israel]]\n| {{Currency|2043|USD}} (~{{Currency|8000|ILS}}), where payments can be made either in [[Israeli New Shekel|ILS]] or in [[United States Dollar|US$]].\n|-\n| [[Russia]]\n| {{Currency|150000|RUB}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|150000|RUS|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Taiwan]]\n| {{Currency|160000|TWD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|160000|TWN|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|160000|TWD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|160000|TWN|round=yes}}}}) Note: minimum annual income ({{Currency|3500000|TWD}})<ref>Taiwan TV news 2015-11-24 on department clerk leaking client's card on FaceBook</ref>\n|-\n| [[Lebanon]]\n| {{Currency|3000|LBP}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|3000|USA|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[United Arab Emirates]] \n| {{Currency|11000|AED}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|3000|USA|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Sweden]]\n| {{Currency|30000|SEK}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|30000|SWE|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of ({{Currency|{{To USD|30000|SWE|round=yes}}}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/se/content/pdf/Proprietary_Medlemsvillkor.pdf|title=Medlemsvillkor f\u00f6r American Express\u00ae - Kort|date=2017-06-26|accessdate=2017-06-26}}</ref> \n|}\n\n===Benefits===\nThe card, available for personal and business use, offers services such as a dedicated [[concierge]] and [[Travel agency|travel agent]]; complimentary companion airline tickets on international flights on selected airlines with the purchase of a full-fare ticket; [[personal shopper]]s at retailers such as Dot & Vic's Rathon Station, [[Gucci]], [[Escada]], and [[Saks Fifth Avenue]]; access to [[Airport lounge|airport clubs]]; first-class flight upgrades; membership in [[Sony]]'s Cierge personal shopping program and dozens of other elite club memberships.<ref name=\"Luxury\"/>\n\nHotel benefits include one free night, when at least one paid night is booked during the same stay, in every [[Mandarin Oriental]] hotel worldwide once a year<ref name=\"Luxury\"/> (except for the New York City property),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/australia/icc/hotels/centurion_partner_hotels/centurion_partner_hotels.shtml|title=American Express|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724105045/https://www.americanexpress.com/australia/icc/hotels/centurion_partner_hotels/centurion_partner_hotels.shtml|archivedate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> and privileges at hotel chains like [[Ritz-Carlton]], [[Leading Hotels of the World]], and [[Amanresorts]]. \n\nThe card also features complimentary enrollment in Easirent Car Hire Platinum Service and the [[Avis Rent a Car]] President's Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creditcardforum.com/american-express/330-official-amex-centurion-black-card-guide.html |title=Official American Express Centurion Card Interactive Tour|access-date=2008-12-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708203357/http://creditcardforum.com/american-express/330-official-amex-centurion-black-card-guide.html|archive-date=2011-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSome Centurion customers have purchased automobiles using the card or made purchases exceeding \u20ac1 million (US$1.12 million).{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} The card has no preset limit in theory. In practice the authorization is decided upon past payment and spending patterns; the largest purchase ever made on one was US$170 million for Amedeo Modigliani's \"[[Nu couch\u00e9]]\" painting purchased at a Christie's auction house by [[Liu Yiqian]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Family will fly free for life after $170m purchase on American Express black card|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_29155117/family-will-fly-free-life-after-170m-purchase|work=[[Mercury News]]|accessdate=2015-11-24}}</ref> It was suggested that the reason for funding the purchase through the credit card was to circumvent Chinese money laws that restrict the transfer of money by citizens out of the country to just $50,000.<ref>{{cite web|date=2015|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2015/11/23/billionaire-buys-170m-painting-with-credit-card.html|title=Thestar.com}}</ref>\n\nCenturion Card members, like [[Platinum Card]] members, get complimentary access to the American Express Centurion Lounges at several US airports. They also get unlimited access to [[Priority Pass]] lounges around the world,<ref>{{cite web|date=2016|url=http://iwandered.net/2016/11/12/amex-centurion-card-benefits/|title=American Express Centurion Card Benefits}}</ref> plus additional lounge privileges based on the country their card is registered in. For example, Centurion cardholders in Canada also receive full access to Maple Leaf Lounges, a lounge network provided by Air Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yoreoyster.com/blog/american-express-black-centurion-card-canada/|title=Amex Centurion \u2018Black\u2019 Card - The Complete Guide|date=2019-09-20|website=Yore Oyster|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> At busy times, Centurion members have access to areas reserved for them. There are also drink options at the bar that are exclusive to Centurion members. As of 2015, they have a Champagne option of [[Veuve Clicquot]] and a single malt scotch by [[Balvenie]].<ref>{{cite web|website=fhrnews.com|url=https://www.fhrnews.com/news/american-express-black-card-what-is-this-secret-card|title=American Express Black Card: What Is This Secret Card?}}</ref>\n\n===Publications===\nSince the inception of the card, members have received a copy of ''[[Departures (magazine)|Departures]]'', which is also sent to all Platinum Card cardholders. In 2004, American Express Centurion members in the US began receiving an exclusive \"no name\" magazine, which was not available by any other means. Starting with the Spring 2007 edition, this magazine was officially titled '''''Black Ink'''''. The magazine is available only to individual Centurion cardholders, not to the business-edition customers.\n\nEuropean, Asian, and Australian Centurion members receive quarterly the ''[[Centurion (magazine)|Centurion]]'' magazine published by Journal International GmbH (Munich, Germany).<ref name=cen>{{cite journal|title=About Us|journal=Centurion|url=http://www.centurion-magazine.com/about-us/magazine.html|accessdate=19 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817131723/http://www.centurion-magazine.com/about-us/magazine.html|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref> In June 2011, the ''Centurion'' magazine website was launched, offering daily updates for Centurion Card members. According to Journal International, the average age of a ''Centurion'' reader from Europe or the Middle East is 49 years. ''Centurion'' has been published since 2001 and has a circulation in Europe and the Middle East of 44,100, in Asia of 13,900, and in Australia of 6,000.<ref name=\"adinternational.be\"/>\n\n===Elite cards ===\nThe Centurion Card is part of an elite credit card segment created for a very small and exclusive range of clients around the world.<ref name=\"Luxury\"/> Other such cards include:\n\n*[[Palladium Card]]\n\n==Amex Black Card vs. Black Card==\n[[Luxury Card]] successfully registered \"Black Card\" as a U.S. [[trademark]] in 2009. [[American Express]] later sued as the name was similar to its [[Centurion Card]], which it contended was widely known as \"the Black Card.\"<ref>[https://www.scribd.com/doc/27692665/Complaint-Black-Card American Express v. Black Card LLC - Complaint and Jury Demand], February 20, 2010; retrieved from [[Scribd]], July 2, 2010</ref> The U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York ruling that Black Card, LLC's trademark of the name \"Black Card\" should be canceled on grounds that it was merely descriptive.<ref>[http://www.vegastrademarkattorney.com/2011/11/amex-wins-cancellation-of-blackcard.html] AMEX Wins Cancellation of BLACKCARD Trademark Registration, Ryan Gile, November 22, 2011</ref> As of 2019, it uses the registered trademark under license.<ref name=footer>{{cite web|url=http://www.luxurycard.com/blackcard|title=MasterCard Black Card}}Footer.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.centurion.com}}\n\n{{American Express}}\n{{Credit cards}}\n\n[[Category:American Express]]\n[[Category:Credit cards]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n[[Category:1999 introductions]]\n[[Category:Credit cards in the United States]]\n\n[[de:American Express#Besonderheiten]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Invitation-only charge card issued by American Express}}\n{{self-published|date=November 2018}}\n[[File:Centurion Card Invitation Set.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Hong Kong Centurion Invitation Kit]]\n\nThe''' American Express Centurion Card''', known informally as the '''Amex Black Card''', is an invitation-only [[charge card]] issued by [[American Express]].<ref>Sullivan, Paul, [http://bucks.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/24/american-express-new-service-for-its-wealthiest-cardholders/ \"American Express\u2019s New Service for Its Wealthiest Cardholders\"], ''The New York Times'', January 24, 2011</ref> An invitation is extended to Platinum Card holders after they meet certain criteria. The Centurion Card comes in personal, business, and corporate variants.<ref name=\"adinternational.be\">[https://archive.is/20131024173057/http://www.adinternational.be/pdf_rest/Platinum_Centurion_Euro  pe.pdf American Express Centurion/Departures] - Media Kit, Europe & Middle East 2010</ref>  \n\n==History==\nIn 1999, American Express introduced the Centurion Card to cater to the very wealthy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerry Seinfeld|website=thepointsguy.com|url=https://thepointsguy.com/news/jerry-seinfeld-amex-black-card/}}</ref> The card was initially available only to selected users of the company's Platinum Card. To become a Centurion cardholder, one must meet American Express eligibility criteria. Cardholders are required to pay an annual fee, and in some countries also an initiation fee.<ref name=\"Luxury\">{{cite book | title=Luxury Brand Management | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | author=Chevalier, Michel | year=2012 | location=Singapore | isbn=978-1-118-17176-9}}</ref> In addition to a variety of benefits, starting in 2015 in some markets, the card itself is made of [[anodize]]d [[titanium]]<ref name=\"Luxury\"/> with the information and numbers [[Laser etching|laser etched]] into the metal. In some locations, such as Israel, [[EMV]] \"chip\" plastic cards, which also include the [[ExpressPay]] [[contactless payment]] technology, are issued. American Express created the card line amid rumors and [[urban legend]]s in the 1980s that it produced an ultra-exclusive black card for elite users who could purchase anything with it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/business/bank/blackcard.asp|publisher=Snopes.com|title=Black American Express Card|date=December 6, 2006|accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Famous cardholders===\n\nAmerican Express does not disclose a list of Centurion cardholders but a number of celebrities have been associated with the card.<ref>{{cite web|website=zimbio.com|url=https://www.zimbio.com/Celebs+Who+Roll+with+the+AmEx+Black+Card|title=Celebs Who Roll with the Amex Black Card}}</ref>\n\nDuring the filming of a backstage interview at the [[2007 BRIT Awards]], [[Noel Gallagher]] held his Centurion card up to the camera and said \"You have to earn a ridiculous amount of money per year to own one of those.\"<ref>{{cite web|website=youtube.com|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DrVqmFY0Lk8#action=share|title=I bet you haven't got one!!!}}</ref> In a 2009 interview with [[talkSPORT]], Gallagher said \"I do own a black Amex card that has unlimited credit and cannot be denied anywhere. I could walk into a showroom selling [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747s]] and, regardless of whether I could afford it, they'd have to accept the card.\" \n\nFormer ''[[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' presenter [[Jeremy Clarkson]] wrote in a 2004 article for ''[[The Times of London]]'' newspaper that he lied about his salary to obtain a Centurion card after reading \"an interview with some chap who'd got a fist full of cards in his pocket and claimed that the more shiny examples, specifically the much-coveted black American Express, gave him certain privileges.\" Clarkson ultimately decides to cancel the card after being unimpressed with its benefits.<ref>{{cite web|website=thetimes.co.uk|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jeremy-clarkson-im-a-nobody-my-jet-set-credit-card-tells-me-so-ftg88kn7j5p|title=Jeremy Clarkson: I\u0092m a nobody, my jet set credit card tells me so}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n\nThe Centurion card has become a [[status symbol]] in the music industry, especially in [[hip-hop culture]].<ref>{{cite web|website=hiphopdx.com|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.9297/title.hip-hops-love-of-the-black-card-celebrated-online|title=Hip Hop's Love Of The Black Card Celebrated Online}}</ref> In 2002, ''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported that rapper [[Sean Combs|Sean \"P. Diddy\" Combs]] used the card to buy 400 cocktails at a bar in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|website=the.honoluluadvertiser.com|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/Apr/14/bz/bz22a.html|title=American Express markets elite 'black card'}}</ref> In the song \"Doing It Way Big\" (2003), [[Lil' Kim]] sings: ''I smack niggas 'cross the face with a Centurion card / Who don't believe I'm (doing it way big).'' Lil' Kim later posed with a Centurion card attached to a diamond-studded necklace for a ''[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]'' magazine photoshoot.<ref>{{cite web|website=tumblr.com|url=https://lilkimuk.tumblr.com/post/65069524969/full-article-lil-kim-nylon-magazine-2003|title=Full Article Lil Kim Nylon Magazine 2003}}</ref> In the song \"Last Call\" (2004), [[Kanye West]] refers to the card with the lyrics: ''I went to the malls and I balled too hard / \"Oh my god, is that a black card?\" / I turned around and replied, \"Why yes / But I prefer the term African American Express\"''. In \"[[Welcome Back (Mase song)|Welcome Back]]\" (2004), [[Mase]] sings: ''Amex black card / Shopper of the year''. In \"Get It Poppin'\" (2005), [[Fat Joe]] sings: ''I got that black no limit American Express card''. Other singers including [[Ariana Grande]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Lady Gaga]], [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Bow Wow]], [[Nelly Furtado]] and [[Lil Wayne]] also mention black cards in their song lyrics but not a specific American Express product.\n\n===Film and TV===\n\nThe Centurion card has been used as an on-screen prop. In ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'', [[James Bond]] hands a Centurion card to a travel agent with a private jet chartering company to pay for a flight to Bolivia. The payment is declined by [[MI6]] as the intelligence service seeks to strip Bond of his duties and revokes his credit cards and passports. The Centurion replica used in the film was part of the Bond in Motion exhibition at the [[London Film Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|website=jamesbondlifestyle.com|url=https://www.jamesbondlifestyle.com/product/american-express-centurion-card|title=American Express Centurion Card}}</ref>\n\nIn the pilot episode of the [[USA Network]] medical comedy-drama show ''[[Royal Pains]]'', Tucker Bryant, the young heir to a family fortune earned from inventing the blender, injures himself crashing his father\u2019s Ferrari. He tells a doctor to \"go into my wallet and get the little black card that says American Express on it\" and flies by helicopter from the Hamptons to Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan. In an episode of the [[NBC]] crime-drama show ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', one character is described as \"by the look of his black American Express, very rich.\"\n\n===Literature===\n\nIn [[Lauren Weisberger]]'s novel ''[[Everyone Worth Knowing]]'', the protagonist Bette remarks on her coworker paying for dinner with the card: \"There it was, the mythical American Express black card. Available by invitation only to those who charged a minimum of $150,000 per year.\"<ref>{{cite web|website=books.google.co.uk|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wAoF693o-fEC&pg=PA80&dq=Lauren+Weisberger+American+Express+black&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBwLXdtMzoAhVCiFwKHaZIDzUQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=Lauren%20Weisberger%20American%20Express%20black&f=false|title=Everyone Worth Knowing}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Robert Crais]]'s novel ''[[The Watchman (Crais novel)|The Watchman]]'', the daughter of a wealthy businessman is described as having a Centurion card.<ref>{{cite web|website=books.google.co.uk|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_LSQXOkOo14C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=robert+crais+black+amex&source=bl&ots=CHGFuanYXT&sig=ACfU3U3X35XUgqaQup42-vltT-F5Z0qNlg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi5n4jVs8zoAhUGY8AKHfi7BCkQ6AEwAHoECBAQKQ#v=onepage&q=robert%20crais%20black%20amex&f=false|title=The Watchman: A Joe Pike Novel}}</ref> \n\n==Features==\n===Availability and fees===\nThe Centurion Card is invitation-only after appropriate [[net worth]] with American Express, credit, and spending criteria are met.<ref name=\"Luxury\"/> American Express does not publicly disclose the requirements necessary for getting or keeping a card, except that the cardholder needs to have a substantial net worth, as well as having been a Platinum card holder.<ref name=\"Luxury\"/>\n\nWhile the eligibility criteria are subject to speculation, most reliable sources agree that Centurion Card holders have historically spent US$250,000 or more per year on lower-level American Express cards.<ref name=\"frankel\">{{Cite web |last=Frankel |first=Matthew |date=24 August 2014 |title=Is The American Express Black Card Really Worth It? The Centurion card, or 'black card', is the most exclusive credit card in the world, but is it worth the high cost? |url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/08/24/is-the-american-express-black-card-really-worth-it.aspx |publisher=[[The Motley Fool]] |access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Centurion Card annual fees\n|-\n! Country/Region !! Annual fee/limit\n|-\n\n| [[United States]]\n| {{Currency|5000|}} ({{Currency|2500}} for each additional card member) plus one-time joining fee of {{Currency|10000|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/content/dam/amex/us/staticassets/pdf/cardmember-agreements/centurion/centurion-card-11-01-2019.pdf|title=Cardmember Agreement|last=|first=|date=2019-11-16|website=|publisher=American Express|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.americanexpress.com/content/dam/amex/us/staticassets/pdf/cardmember-agreements/centurion/centurion-card-11-01-2019.pdf|archive-date=2015-09-10|accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| {{Currency|2200|GBP}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|2200|GBR|round=yes}}}}) (unlimited) plus one-time joining fee of {{Currency|2500|GBP}}\n|-\n| [[Canada]]\n| {{Currency|2500|CAD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|2500|CAN|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|5000|CAD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|5000|CAN|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[India]]\n| {{Currency|200000|INR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|200000|IND|round=yes}}}}) plus one time fees of {{Currency|250000|INR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|250000|IND|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[France]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Netherlands]]\n| {{Currency|3000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|3000|FRA|round=yes}}}}) plus one time fee \u20ac3,000 (Italy, Netherlands)\n|-\n| [[Germany]], [[Austria]]\n| {{Currency|5000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|5000|DEU|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|4000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4000|DEU|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Switzerland]]\n| {{Currency|4200|CHF}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4200|CHE|round=yes}}}}) (unlimited)\n|-\n| [[Australia]]\n| {{Currency|5000|AUD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|5000|AUS|round=yes}}}}) (increased from {{Currency|4300|AUD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4300|AUS|round=yes}}}}), effective 11 July 2012) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|5000|AUD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|5000|AUS|round=yes}}}}), effective 11 July 2012\n|-\n| [[Japan]]\n| {{Currency|365000|JPY}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|365000|JPN|round=yes}}}}) (increased from {{Currency|197000|JPY}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|197000|JPN|round=yes}}}}), effective 1 January 2008) \n|-\n| [[Hong Kong]]\n| {{Currency|38800|HKD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|38800|HKG|round=yes}}}}) plus one time fee of {{To USD|38800|HKG|round=yes}} (increase from {{Currency|19800|HKD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|19800|HKG|round=yes}}}}), effective 30 May 2013)\n|-\n| [[South Korea]] ([[Republic of Korea]])\n| {{Currency|3000000|KRW}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|3000000|KOR|round=yes}}}}), unlimited\n|-\n| [[China]] ([[People's Republic of China]])\n| {{Currency|18000|CNY}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|18000|CHN|round=yes}}}}) issued by [[Industrial and Commercial Bank of China]] (ICBC) and [[China Merchants Bank]] (CMB) pursuant to a license from American Express. <br />{{Currency|36000|CNY}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|36000|CHN|round=yes}}}}) issued by [[China Minsheng Bank]] (CMBC) pursuant to a license from American Express. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/epaper/2015-06/29/content_21133960.htm|title=Minsheng to offer new Amex cards{{!}}Business{{!}}chinadaily.com.cn|website=usa.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Singapore]]\n| {{Currency|7490|SGD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|7490|SGP|round=yes}}}}) (unlimited) plus one-time joining fee of {{Currency|7490|SGD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|7490|SGP|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Kuwait]]\n|{{Currency|{{To USD|4000|USA|round=yes}}}} for Titanium-based Centurion. Issued by [[American Express]] [[Middle East]] ([[Bahrain]]) (Same applies for [[Bahrain]], [[United Arab Emirates]], and [[Qatar]])\n|-\n| [[Mexico]]\n| {{Currency|56000|MXN}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|56000|MEX|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Brazil]]\n| {{Currency|4250|BRL}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4250|BRA|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Argentina]]\n| {{Currency|20000|ARS}} ({{Currency| {{To USD|20000|ARG|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| {{Currency|15000|SAR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|15000|SAU|round=yes}}|}}) (unlimited)\n|-\n| International Dollar Currency Card (IDC)\n| {{Currency|3000|USD}} ({{Currency|0|USD}} for the first additional card member, {{Currency|1500|USD}} for each additional card member thereafter) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|5000|USD}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/content/dam/amex/us/staticassets/pdf/cardmember-agreements/centurion-idc/idc-centurion-09-30-2019.pdf|title=Cardmember Agreement - The Centurion\u00ae Card - International Dollar Card|date=2019-09-30|accessdate=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| International Euro Currency Card (IEC)\n| {{Currency|4000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4000|DEU|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|4000|EUR}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|4000|DEU|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Israel]]\n| {{Currency|2043|USD}} (~{{Currency|8000|ILS}}), where payments can be made either in [[Israeli New Shekel|ILS]] or in [[United States Dollar|US$]].\n|-\n| [[Russia]]\n| {{Currency|150000|RUB}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|150000|RUS|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Taiwan]]\n| {{Currency|160000|TWD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|160000|TWN|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of {{Currency|160000|TWD}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|160000|TWN|round=yes}}}}) Note: minimum annual income ({{Currency|3500000|TWD}})<ref>Taiwan TV news 2015-11-24 on department clerk leaking client's card on FaceBook</ref>\n|-\n| [[Lebanon]]\n| {{Currency|3000|LBP}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|3000|USA|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[United Arab Emirates]] \n| {{Currency|11000|AED}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|3000|USA|round=yes}}}})\n|-\n| [[Sweden]]\n| {{Currency|30000|SEK}} ({{Currency|{{To USD|30000|SWE|round=yes}}}}) plus one-time fee of ({{Currency|{{To USD|30000|SWE|round=yes}}}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/se/content/pdf/Proprietary_Medlemsvillkor.pdf|title=Medlemsvillkor f\u00f6r American Express\u00ae - Kort|date=2017-06-26|accessdate=2017-06-26}}</ref> \n|}\n\n===Benefits===\nThe card, available for personal and business use, offers services such as a dedicated [[concierge]] and [[Travel agency|travel agent]]; complimentary companion airline tickets on international flights on selected airlines with the purchase of a full-fare ticket; [[personal shopper]]s at retailers such as Dot & Vic's Rathon Station, [[Gucci]], [[Escada]], and [[Saks Fifth Avenue]]; access to [[Airport lounge|airport clubs]]; first-class flight upgrades; membership in [[Sony]]'s Cierge personal shopping program and dozens of other elite club memberships.<ref name=\"Luxury\"/>\n\nHotel benefits include one free night, when at least one paid night is booked during the same stay, in every [[Mandarin Oriental]] hotel worldwide once a year<ref name=\"Luxury\"/> (except for the New York City property),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanexpress.com/australia/icc/hotels/centurion_partner_hotels/centurion_partner_hotels.shtml|title=American Express|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724105045/https://www.americanexpress.com/australia/icc/hotels/centurion_partner_hotels/centurion_partner_hotels.shtml|archivedate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> and privileges at hotel chains like [[Ritz-Carlton]], [[Leading Hotels of the World]], and [[Amanresorts]]. \n\nThe card also features complimentary enrollment in Easirent Car Hire Platinum Service and the [[Avis Rent a Car]] President's Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creditcardforum.com/american-express/330-official-amex-centurion-black-card-guide.html |title=Official American Express Centurion Card Interactive Tour|access-date=2008-12-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708203357/http://creditcardforum.com/american-express/330-official-amex-centurion-black-card-guide.html|archive-date=2011-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSome Centurion customers have purchased automobiles using the card or made purchases exceeding \u20ac1 million (US$1.12 million).{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} The card has no preset limit in theory. In practice the authorization is decided upon past payment and spending patterns; the largest purchase ever made on one was US$170 million for Amedeo Modigliani's \"[[Nu couch\u00e9]]\" painting purchased at a Christie's auction house by [[Liu Yiqian]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Family will fly free for life after $170m purchase on American Express black card|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_29155117/family-will-fly-free-life-after-170m-purchase|work=[[Mercury News]]|accessdate=2015-11-24}}</ref> It was suggested that the reason for funding the purchase through the credit card was to circumvent Chinese money laws that restrict the transfer of money by citizens out of the country to just $50,000.<ref>{{cite web|date=2015|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2015/11/23/billionaire-buys-170m-painting-with-credit-card.html|title=Thestar.com}}</ref>\n\nCenturion Card members, like [[Platinum Card]] members, get complimentary access to the American Express Centurion Lounges at several US airports. They also get unlimited access to [[Priority Pass]] lounges around the world,<ref>{{cite web|date=2016|url=http://iwandered.net/2016/11/12/amex-centurion-card-benefits/|title=American Express Centurion Card Benefits}}</ref> plus additional lounge privileges based on the country their card is registered in. For example, Centurion cardholders in Canada also receive full access to Maple Leaf Lounges, a lounge network provided by Air Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yoreoyster.com/blog/american-express-black-centurion-card-canada/|title=Amex Centurion \u2018Black\u2019 Card - The Complete Guide|date=2019-09-20|website=Yore Oyster|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> At busy times, Centurion members have access to areas reserved for them. There are also drink options at the bar that are exclusive to Centurion members. As of 2015, they have a Champagne option of [[Veuve Clicquot]] and a single malt scotch by [[Balvenie]].<ref>{{cite web|website=fhrnews.com|url=https://www.fhrnews.com/news/american-express-black-card-what-is-this-secret-card|title=American Express Black Card: What Is This Secret Card?}}</ref>\n\n===Publications===\nSince the inception of the card, members have received a copy of ''[[Departures (magazine)|Departures]]'', which is also sent to all Platinum Card cardholders. In 2004, American Express Centurion members in the US began receiving an exclusive \"no name\" magazine, which was not available by any other means. Starting with the Spring 2007 edition, this magazine was officially titled '''''Black Ink'''''. The magazine is available only to individual Centurion cardholders, not to the business-edition customers.\n\nEuropean, Asian, and Australian Centurion members receive quarterly the ''[[Centurion (magazine)|Centurion]]'' magazine published by Journal International GmbH (Munich, Germany).<ref name=cen>{{cite journal|title=About Us|journal=Centurion|url=http://www.centurion-magazine.com/about-us/magazine.html|accessdate=19 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817131723/http://www.centurion-magazine.com/about-us/magazine.html|archivedate=17 August 2013}}</ref> In June 2011, the ''Centurion'' magazine website was launched, offering daily updates for Centurion Card members. According to Journal International, the average age of a ''Centurion'' reader from Europe or the Middle East is 49 years. ''Centurion'' has been published since 2001 and has a circulation in Europe and the Middle East of 44,100, in Asia of 13,900, and in Australia of 6,000.<ref name=\"adinternational.be\"/>\n\n===Elite cards ===\nThe Centurion Card is part of an elite credit card segment created for a very small and exclusive range of clients around the world.<ref name=\"Luxury\"/> Other such cards include:\n\n*[[Palladium Card]]\n\n==Amex Black Card vs. Black Card==\n[[Luxury Card]] successfully registered \"Black Card\" as a U.S. [[trademark]] in 2009. [[American Express]] later sued as the name was similar to its [[Centurion Card]], which it contended was widely known as \"the Black Card.\"<ref>[https://www.scribd.com/doc/27692665/Complaint-Black-Card American Express v. Black Card LLC - Complaint and Jury Demand], February 20, 2010; retrieved from [[Scribd]], July 2, 2010</ref> The U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York ruling that Black Card, LLC's trademark of the name \"Black Card\" should be canceled on grounds that it was merely descriptive.<ref>[http://www.vegastrademarkattorney.com/2011/11/amex-wins-cancellation-of-blackcard.html] AMEX Wins Cancellation of BLACKCARD Trademark Registration, Ryan Gile, November 22, 2011</ref> As of 2019, it uses the registered trademark under license.<ref name=footer>{{cite web|url=http://www.luxurycard.com/blackcard|title=MasterCard Black Card}}Footer.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.centurion.com}}\n\n{{American Express}}\n{{Credit cards}}\n\n[[Category:American Express]]\n[[Category:Credit cards]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n[[Category:1999 introductions]]\n[[Category:Credit cards in the United States]]\n\n[[de:American Express#Besonderheiten]]\n", "name_user": "Sdubu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expands history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centurion_Card"}
{"title_page": "Albazino mine", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox mine\n| name = Albazino mine\n| state/province = [[Khabarovsk Krai]]\n| country = [[Russia]]\n| products = [[Gold]]\n| subdivision_type =\n}}\n\nThe '''Albazino mine''' is one of the largest [[gold]] mines in [[Russia]] and in the world. The mine is located in [[Khabarovsk Krai]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Basov|first=Vladimir|url=https://www.mining.com/highest-grade-gold-mines-2017/|title=Highest-grade gold mines in 2017|date=10 September 2018|work=Mining.com|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. The mine has estimated reserves of 5.3 million oz of [[gold]]. It is mined by conventional truck-shovel and drill-and-blast methods<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://miningdataonline.com/property/3444/Albazino-Mine.aspx|title=Major Mines & Projects {{!}} Albazino Mine|website=miningdataonline.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Khabarovsk Krai}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albazino Mine}}\n[[Category:Gold mines in Russia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Khabarovsk Krai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox mine\n| name = Albazino mine\n| state/province = [[Khabarovsk Krai]]\n| country = [[Russia]]\n| products = [[Gold]]\n| subdivision_type =\n}}\n\nThe '''Albazino mine''' is one of the largest [[gold]] mines in [[Russia]] and in the world. The mine is located in [[Khabarovsk Krai]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Basov|first=Vladimir|url=https://www.mining.com/highest-grade-gold-mines-2017/|title=Highest-grade gold mines in 2017|date=10 September 2018|work=Mining.com|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. The mine has estimated reserves of 5.3 million oz of [[gold]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Khabarovsk Krai}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albazino Mine}}\n[[Category:Gold mines in Russia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Khabarovsk Krai]]\n", "name_user": "Plidigiworld", "label": "safe"